s and the privileged still manipulate the rhetoric of conquest to justify and serve their own worldly ends. For colonized peoples who live today at the "ends of the earth," the age of exploitation may be no different from the age of exploration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aProphecyxChristianity. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aage of exploration.  aatlantic.  aclaim and conquer.  acolonialism.  acolumbus.  acountrymen.  adecolonization.  adivine predestination.  aempire.  aends of the earth.  aeuropean adventurers.  aexploitation.  afounding doctrines.  alanguage of prophecy.  alegion.  aliterary criticism theory.  aliterary theory.  anew world.  apostcolonial era.  aprivileged.  areligious beliefs.  arhetoric.  aricher nations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007442240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520911338?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911338/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles